  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;kindness&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Elizabeth s Family &lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;Our lovely mum was brought into A and E at 1 am late november. we were told that she had suffered a non survivable stroke. staff managed to find us a quiet corner in a hectic department so our family could start to gather. later mum was transferred to ward A10 where she would receive end of life care for the next 7 days. mum was in her own room and the ward staff allowed unrestricted visiting and put a bed up in the room so my brother and sister could stay overnight  so that mum was never alone. throughout those 7 long days and nights mum was cared for with the utmost kindness by everyone who came into contact with her. consultant s , auxiliary staff and the 
amazing nurses who gently turned, cleaned and administered the meds so that mum was comfortable, calm and  blessedly pain free. everyone had time to travel to come and say goodbye and were  made very welcome on the ward . we had a perfumed scarf on mums pillow in case she could still smell and feel comforted and my daughter drew a little picture for her.the staff taped the picture to mums pillow each time they turned her and put the scarf back near to her. these small things showed great kindness and compassion and meant a great deal  to all of us. when mum passed away we were not hurried and encouraged to spend as much time with her as needed. I thought i would find it very difficult to drive away that final night but in fact felt that mum was still in caring and kind hands and left with peace of mind. we will be forever grateful and  send our sincere thanks to all ....the paramedics, the A and E staff and the whole wonderful team on A10 .&lt;/CommentText&gt;
